  "prompt": "Is Prime Minister of India a constitutional post?",
  "response": "Yes, the Prime Minister of India is a constitutional post. The Prime Minister is the head of the government and is responsible for the administration of the country. The role and powers of the Prime Minister are defined in the Constitution of India, primarily in Articles 75 through 78. The Prime Minister is appointed by the President of India and is typically the leader of the party or coalition that has a majority in the Lok Sabha (the lower house of Parliament). The Constitution outlines the responsibilities of the Prime Minister, including advising the President, leading the Cabinet, and representing the government in the Parliament.",
